Colman, who follows this reading, rendere it: “ Madam, if so, my master gains a loss;'' with this note: The most indifferent parts of an author commonly give the most trouble. The sense of the original being somewhat dark, and the best con- struction not very elegant, several attempts have been made to amend and alter the text. In this, as in most other cases, I believe the common reading to be the right one; and that it contains nothing more than a conceit from a slave, founded on the words damno auem, which I have endeavoured to render in the manner of the original, “gains a loss.” Some think by herus is meant Clitipho, others Chremes. Eugraphius explains the words to signify that Clitipho will be a loser by a new-found sister, who will be co-heiress; and others will have them to imply the loss to be sustained by Chremes in paying Antiphila’s portion.
